YOU ASK ME EVERY YEAR, SO HERE IT IS. 🥚🥚🥚

MJ’s NEW ENGLAND MAPLE EGGNOG

{Add your fave b🚫🚫ze if ya please or keep it PG} 

Shake well and often. I like to drink within 48 hours. (But *some* people like to age it up to a few months or more) 🤷🏻‍♂️ 

Serves 12

INGREDIENTS:

12 eggs, separated- with no shells!
3/4 cups granulated sugar
3/4 cups real maple syrup 
1 quart whole, organic milk (if possible)
1 1/2 quarts organic heavy cream (if possible) 
5.5 cups booze if you please- I suggest whiskey if so 
Freshly grated nutmeg, to taste 
{Optional: freshly ground pink peppercorns and/or star anise to taste}

DIRECTIONS:

In a tabletop, electric mixer, whip egg yolks on high until very thick and pale yellow. Turn down speed to medium and gradually add sugar to yolks. Then, while whisking, drizzle in maple syrup.

Next, with mixer on low, whisk in milk and 1 quart heavy cream. If using- add booze, stirring constantly to combine. Set aside. 

Just before serving, clean mixer bowl and whisk egg whites until stiff peaks have formed. Fold gently into mixture. Clean bowl. Now, whip remaining 1/2 quart heavy cream until stiff, and fold in. Sprinkle with freshly grated nutmeg, pink peppercorns and star anise.

Drink up! Happy Yule. 🌲

So in love with these boys. These YOUNG MEN. Watching them grow is my life’s greatest adventure. 

I feel myself get caught up at times with life, work- the trappings of adulthood…WRAPPED up in SELF and my projected fears and insecurities…

This weekend was a wave to wash over me. I’m so grateful. So in awe of them. And so damn blessed to be your dad. I love you, boys. 

Here’s to an adventurous life. 💫

TUNA MELT TUTORIAL

Absolutely NOTHING rivals a proper TUNA MELT on sourdough - don’t even come at me with a rival. All must BOW DOWN to the almighty melt. 💧 

I make mine folded with respectable flavor servants only - Hellman’s mayo, Cholula, some fancy ass German mustard I bought, a fat bump of sweet relish, a f*ckton of freshly cracked pepper, and a hefty spoon of chopped @matiz_foods Piparras peppers. 🌶️ 

Nestle that succulent mound between two perfectly toasted slices of sourdough, drape her with a blanket of Kraft white American cheese, hammer her under the broiler for a hot minute until she’s drip drip, then devour her satiating intricacies, revel in her glory and bask in her glow. 💋

Best performed with a supporting cast of an ice cold root beer with pebble ice and a paper towel for wiping your face hole. I don’t drink soda because it’s the devil- but trust me on that.🥤 

Lookie here. See that? You did that. Doesn’t it feel good to have the best goddamn sandwich on the block? I thought so. 🙌🏻

If you work in #hospitality and/or #realestatedevelopment,
#environmentalengineering or any function adjacent to understanding humans and their relationship to their environments, and you haven’t read this seminal piece on #community and the significance of building the #thirdplace, I can’t recommend it more. 

I’ve loved this book for many years and am on my fourth read right now - every time discovering new nuggets of insight and inspiration. 

In the absence of general stores, local taverns, meeting houses, hardware and feed stores and even the diner counters of the past century, we’re all left to seek community and belonging through our handheld electronic devices, or behind desktop screens. But it’s not the same. 

The concept of a “Third Place” allowed a space for gossiping, joking, disagreeing, arguing, speculating, celebrating, bargaining. A space where uncommon conversations could be had by common people. 

These important “Third Places” offered social discourse, to embrace a healthy reconciliation with one another. But sadly, they’re dying. Why? 

These days we find comfort in building community with those who are likeminded - we join social sites, chat rooms, private groups and text threads that amplify our belief systems, instead of question them. 

We’ve grown apart. Technology has done so much for us - and yet simultaneously - it has broken us down, or perhaps more accurately, exposed the raw nerves that lay just underneath the surface all along. 

How do we get back to a place where we value the creation of these incredibly important venues and gathering spaces? What will it take for developers and those who “control” our public spaces, to realize the significance a well designed and curated Third Place can add to our local community? 

This is the role that restaurants play in our society. They are vital to our collective mental and public health. Facts. They are more than food and drink. They are a community forum, an information center, even an arena of debate. 

Patronize your favorite spaces. Support restaurants. In these places, we are perhaps more truly a community than at any other time.

#supportrestaurants #hospitalityfirst

TODAY I CELEBRATE 7 YEARS SOBER. 🚫🚫🚫🚫🚫‼️‼️‼️

I could easily make a long-winded post about my ongoing work to overcome the struggle of addiction, my continued commitment of reestablishing my relationships, my efforts to create new social norms for myself, or my thirst for empowering others through positive change…but for today- I’ll just say this: 

Life is absolutely awe inspiring and unfolding. It is intricate, nuanced and mystifying. I am so fucking blessed to have my family, my friendships and my faith in continuous personal awakening, as well as my unshakable trust in this path…

I have stepped into the stream of life!! The water is cold, swift, unclouded and FREE. There is deep beauty here. I think I’ll stay. 

To those still struggling: know that there is a sincere love for you, and plenty of room on this side of the bank.

Grateful. Grateful. Grateful. 

I love you. 

💕 MJ

ITS A VIBE ALRIGHT. BIRTHDAY VIBEZ. FOR MEEEEEEEE 🎂

Woke up at the crack of dawn and made myself this…

BANANA CAKE WITH CREAM CHEESE FROSTING AND MARCONA ALMOND CRUMBLE 💅🏼 🍰 

You can make it toooo! 

Ingredients: 

For the cake- 

1.5 C mashed bananas- blacker the better!
3 C AP flour
1 t baking powder
1 t baking soda
1/2 t cinnamon
1/2 t kosher salt
3/4 C unsalted butter, room temp 
1 C granulated sugar
1/2 C packed light sugar
3 large eggs, room temperature
2 t pure vanilla extract
1.5 C buttermilk, room temp

For the frosting-

8 oz. block cream cheese, room temp
1/2 C unsalted butter, room temp
3 C confectioners’ sugar, plus an extra 1/4 cup if needed
1 t pure vanilla extract
1/8 t salt

Procedure: 

Preheat oven to 350°F & grease a 9×13-inch pan.

Make the cake: Mash bananas. Set aside.
Whisk flour, baking powder, baking soda, cinnamon, & salt together. Set aside.
Using stand mixer fitted with a paddle attachment, beat butter on high until smooth & creamy – about 1 min. Add both sugars & beat on high for 2 mins until creamed together. 

Scrape down sides of bowl with rubber spatula as needed. Add eggs and vanilla. Beat on medium-high until combined, then beat in mashed bananas. Scrape down sides of bowl as needed. With mixer on low, add dry ingredients in three additions alternating with buttermilk & mixing each addition until just incorporated. DON’T OVERMIX. Batter will be slightly thick and a few lumps is OK. I MEAN- LIFE HAS LOTS OF LUMPS AND WE GET THROUGH IT! 😉 

Spread batter prepared pan. Bake 45–50 mins. Cake is done when toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. Remove cake from oven & set on wire rack. Cool completely. 

Make frosting- 

In large bowl of stand mixer, beat room temp cream cheese & butter together until whipped. Add confectioners sugar, vanilla and salt. Beat on low first, then high to thicken. 

Frost the cake. Sprinkle with crushed marcona almonds. DIG IN.

Going into the long weekend grateful to those who have sacrificed- often with their lives, so that we can play baseball, cook in a barn, and raise two boys in this beautiful place we call home. 

Freedom is a gift and a blessing, and while the desire for personal freedom might be innate, it is certainly not guaranteed. 

At a time when personal freedoms are under siege all over the world- including right here at home- and our global consciousness reflects a palpable disquietude, we should take solace in community, relationships and the power of unconditional love. 

Thank you to those who came before us to allow these freedoms and those who continue to protect our personal harmonies- by the sword or by the pen. We recognize how blessed we are and will never take it for granted. 🇺🇸 ☸️ ☮️

WHAT IS WRONG WITH ALL OF YOU.

It’s funny how you spend so much time as a young parent, trying to inspire your kids to love what you love. 

For me it was music, cooking, the arts, mountain sports, nature…knowing full well all along that they are their own humans and that, ultimately, they will write their own story. But at one time- attempting to inform that story, felt like a parental duty. 

And yet, at some point as parents, we relinquish the concept of having “control” over the people our children will become. For they are indeed - and uniquely- their own people. 

It’s no wonder then, that no longer before you have abandoned the idea of helping mold them, they start to surprise you in the wildest ways- making you proud, curios and joyful that you are even blessed enough to watch their blossoming in real time. 

All this to say, the countless rainy hikes I’ve taken by myself over the years from the woods of the Pacific Northwest to the hills of Piemonte with brown bag and pocket knife in hand, have culminated in a simple question from Sawyer today: 

“Dad, can we go foraging?” 

You’re goddamned right we can, son. 

Love these boys. And love watching them blossom.

It’s almost that time of year…pumpkins, squash and SWEET POTATOES!! 🍠🍠🍠

I know, I know. You don’t want to hear it. It’s the end of summer! BUT if you want an awesome, simple recipe to send you into autumnal heaven, it’s my SWEET POTATO GNOCCHI. 

The best part? Make these babies ahead and freeze them. Once frozen, put them in sandwich bags and pull them out for easy weeknight dinners. Also- I like mine with Pecorino but you can use Parmesan if you want!

SWEET POTATO GNOCCHI

Serves 4

Ingredients: 

2 sweet potatoes
1 large egg
1/2 C grated Pecorino plus more for serving
3/4 C unbleached AP flour, plus more for rolling
2 T unsalted butter, for frying

Cook potatoes: clean & pierce in several places. Microwave on high until tender, 8 mins. Let cool.

While still warm, slice potatoes lengthwise. Scoop out potato, but don’t get large pieces of skin mixed in. A muffin scoop works awesome!

Place potato flesh into potato ricer with large hole screen & press through. Potato masher or fork works fine too. Should be light and fluffy, as opposed to mashed. You should have about 1 1/4 cups when done.

Cool potato to barely warm. Add egg, mix until combined.

In small bowl, whisk pecorino & flour. With fork, gently work Pecorino & flour into potato mix. Use light touch to keep mixture from becoming dense. You're looking to make a soft dough that just holds together. It's OK if there's flour still left in the bowl; you don't want to knead dough thoroughly.

Cover dough w/ plastic wrap & allow it to rest while you bring 2 qts of water to boil. On another burner, melt 2 T butter in large skillet. You'll need both the water and skillet ready when you start cooking gnocchi, as they cook in just a few mins!

When water is nearly boiling, use bench scraper to divide dough into three tennis ball-sized pieces. Divide those pieces into smaller pieces, about size of your index finger and about 1" long. A “snake”! Cut into “digit” size pieces about the size of the tip of your thumb to your thumb knuckle.

Gently roll each gnocchi in flour to prevent sticking. Using a fork, press grooves into each piece & set aside as you roll more.

NAILED THIS #chickencacciatore over noods 🍝 for the crew tonight. 👨‍👩‍👦‍👦 🍗 

Simple. Rustic. End of summer lovin’. ✅ 

INGREDIENTS:

6 bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs
1 Spanish onion, julienned
10-12 oz. mushrooms, sliced (I like using Baby Bellas cuz they’re easy for weeknight meal! 😚
6 cloves garlic coarsely chopped
1 red bell pepper, julienned 
1/2 t red pepper flakes
1/2 C red wine (or skip the wine like me and use 2 T sherry vinegar)
28 oz. crushed tomatoes
2 T tomato paste
1 t fresh oregano, chopped
2 t fresh rosemary, chopped
1/2 C mixed pitted green olives and oil cured black- or whatever you like
1 t capers, unrinsed
1 t kosher salt to taste 
1/2 t freshly ground black pepper
2 T fresh parsley, roughly chopped
and a few basil leaves

PROCEDURE:

1. Pat chicken dry. Season w/ salt & pepper.  With tablespoon of olive oil sear chicken on medium high heat 3 mins each side, until a golden. Set aside. (If using  chicken with the skin on, it will produce more oil, you can drain oil from pan, if needed, leave about a tablespoon or two in pan.)

2. In same pan, sauté onions, mushrooms in olive oil (or use left over chicken oil!) for 3 mins over medium heat.  Add garlic, bell pepper & red pepper flakes, saute for 1 min more.

3. Lower heat & add wine (vin), crushed tomatoes, tomato paste, oregano, rosemary, olives, capers, salt and pepper.  Stir to fully combine.

4. Place seared chicken in the sauce. Simmer 25 mins. Leave uncovered, though splatter screen is nice as it will sputter a bit! Test the internal temp of chicken, gotta hit 165F! Simmer longer if needed.  Bone-in thighs may take up to 35 mins!

5. Scatter fresh herbs over the top.  Serve over pasta baaaaby!

Sometimes I’m reminded that my career in the kitchen is so much more than cooking. 

The cooking is always there no matter what- like an old, battle tested friendship. An embrace that envelops your body and just…fits. Familiar. Like a knife in your hand. An apron tied around your waist. No matter how long you’ve been away, or how many stories you and the kitchen have to exchange or adventures to recount, it’s always there. Comforting.

But so too, with mentoring and coaching. My life’s greatest accomplishment is now watching others succeed, whom I’ve had some small part in supporting. This means more to me than the food. Because truly leading in a kitchen, means you are teaching life skills, emboldening personal creative pursuits and optimizing growth opportunities for those around you. 

Last night’s dinner @redbarnkitchenvt was very special to me. Chef @jamesfgalbraith and I met under unique circumstances. He was navigating personal changes, establishing new commitments- to himself and his family- seeking balance, and needing someone to listen. 

Fast forward two years and it all came full circle last night when James and I got to cook together for the first time. 

What a life. I’m so blessed to have these moments. It never escapes me. Thank you, James. 

Oh, and the food? Yeah, about that….Goddamn this kid can cook. Keep your eye on him.
